<TABLE border=0 align=center width="80%" cellpadding=1 cellspacing=0>
<tr><td valign=top colspan=5><table border=0 width="100%"><tr><td><font size="+1"><B><a name="148">Bally Derby</a></B> / IPD No. <a class="linkid"  href="machine.cgi?id=148">148</a> <I>/ December 09, 1935 / 1 Player</I></font><br>&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=top></td></tr></table></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=top align=right><b>Average Fun Rating: </b></td><td colspan=4 width="80%" align=left valign=top><font color=red>No ratings on file</font> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;[ <a href="rate/login.pl?gid=148" target="do_a_rating">Be first to rate this game!</a> ]
</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Manufacturer: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><span title="Click here to perform a search for all pinball games manufactured by 'Bally'"><a href="search.pl?searchtype=advanced&amp;mfgid=47">Bally Manufacturing Corporation (1931-1983) <i>[Trade Name: Bally</i>]</a></span></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Project Date: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>December 09, 1935</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Model Number: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>66</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Type: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Electro-mechanical (EM)&nbsp;<a href="showhelp.pl?item=type&amp;highlight=EM#EM" title="Show Type Classifications" target="help"><img alt="[?]" style="cursor: help;" src="/graphic/question.gif" border=0></a></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" align="right" valign=baseline><b>Serial Number Database:</b></td><td colspan=4 align="left" valign=baseline><a href="redirect.pl?http://www.ipsnd.net/View.aspx?id=148">View at <I>The Internet Pinball Serial Number Database</I> (IPSND.net)</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<font size="-1"><I>(External site)</i></font></td></tr><tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Theme: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Horse Racing - Payout</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Specialty: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>One Ball Game&nbsp;<a href="glossary.php#One_Ball_Game" title="Explain this specialty" target="help"><img alt="[?]" style="cursor: help;" src="/graphic/question.gif" border=0></a><br>
Payout Machine&nbsp;<a href="glossary.php#Payout_Machine" title="Explain this specialty" target="help"><img alt="[?]" style="cursor: help;" src="/graphic/question.gif" border=0></a><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Notable Features: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Incorporates "Odds and Payout" units. It dispenses 5 cent coins when a <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Skill_Shot">skill&nbsp;shot</a> is made into a hole on the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">playfield</a>, the amount depending on the current odds. There is an electric motor that drives the payout unit. The odds drum <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Coil">coil</a> is activated when the ball rolls over a <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Leaf_Switch">leaf&nbsp;switch</a> beneath the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">playfield</a>. There is a mechanical timer (similar to a wind up watch) that will run out after about 10 minutes. The timer has a lever which activates a continuity switch. The game originally ran on batteries, but many were converted to run on power outlets via a 110VAC/12VDC transformer. Advertised as 50 inches long by 24 inches wide.</td></tr>
<tr><td width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Design by: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline><span title="Click here to perform a search for all pinball games that 'Bon&nbsp;MacDougall' was connected with."><a href="search.pl?searchtype=advanced&amp;ppl=Bon%20MacDougall">Bon&nbsp;MacDougall</a></span></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" valign=baseline align=right><b>Notes: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>Also available in a ticket model.<br><br>Bally documentation indicates this game had a release (to production) date of 12-9-35.<br><br>The changing odds feature on the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Backglass">backglass</a> was Bally's first use of it, moved from the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Playfield">playfield</a> of <span title="Click here to open a new window and display PAMCO's 1935 'Pamco Parlay'"><a target="game1760" href="machine.cgi?id=1760">PAMCO's 1935 'Pamco Parlay'</a></span> by the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Designer">designer</a> of that Pamco machine, Bon MacDougall, now employed at Bally.<br><br>An Automatic Age ad, Feb-1936 page 75, states "Manufactured under exclusive arrangement with Pacific Amuse. Mfg. Co."<br><br>According to Marketplace Pictorial History, this new changing odds feature marked the beginning of the <a target="glossary" class="glossarylink" href="/glossary.php#Bingo_Machine">bingo&nbsp;machines</a>.<P></td></tr>
<tr><td nowrap width="20%" align=right valign=baseline><b>Photos in: </b></td><td colspan=4 align=left valign=baseline>
Automatic Age, Feb 1936, pages 75 and  111<br>
Marketplace Pictorial History, Page 140, May 1982<br>
<a href="redirect.pl?http://1930s.com/pinball/forsale/AdCat34-35.html" target="booksourcelink">Pinball Ad Catalog Volume 2, 1934-1935</a>, pages 127 and 129<br>
</td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td nowrap width="20%" align="right" valign=baseline><b>Documentation: </b></td><td align=right nowrap> 610 KB</td><td align=left nowrap width="5%">&nbsp;<a href="redirect.pl?http://get.adobe.com/reader/" style="text-decoration:none;">PDF</a>&nbsp;</td><td align=left><a href="https://www.ipdb.org/files/148/Bally_1935_Bally_Derby_Schematics.pdf" onClick="return purchasemanual();">Schematics</a></td><td> [Jesse Kujawa]</td></tr>
